1
00:00:00,231 --> 00:00:01,393
Okay, welcome everybody.

2
00:00:01,453 --> 00:00:03,055
This is the Medford Historical Commission.

3
00:00:03,075 --> 00:00:04,978
Today is Monday, February 13.

4
00:00:06,440 --> 00:00:13,509
And before we get started, I'm just going to read our disclosure that we are required to have for our electronic meeting.

5
00:00:14,752 --> 00:00:21,675
Pursuant to Chapter 20 of the Acts of 2021, this meeting of the City of Medford Historical Commission will be conducted via remote means.

6
00:00:22,276 --> 00:00:27,558
Members of the public who wish to access the meeting may do so by using the Zoom link provided for in the agenda.

7
00:00:27,958 --> 00:00:37,723
No in-person attendance of members of the public will be permitted and public participation in any public hearing during this meeting shall be by remote means only.

8
00:00:40,113 --> 00:00:42,915
Okay, so tonight we have a full agenda.

9
00:00:42,935 --> 00:00:46,778
We're gonna start off with a couple of significance hearings.

10
00:00:47,458 --> 00:00:52,341
So we will start with 28 Grove Street to start for my commissioners.

11
00:00:53,562 --> 00:00:58,445
Last month, we accepted an application for demolition at this property.

12
00:00:58,465 --> 00:01:00,066
The application was accepted.

13
00:01:00,567 --> 00:01:04,489
So tonight we will determine whether or not the building is historically significant.

14
00:01:05,210 --> 00:01:07,131
And I will remind everybody what that means.

15
00:01:08,347 --> 00:01:12,095
The definition of historical significance is as follows.

16
00:01:12,616 --> 00:01:19,271
It is importantly associated with one or more historic persons or events, or with the broad architectural, cultural,

17
00:01:19,681 --> 00:01:37,169
political, economic, or social history of the city or the Commonwealth, or it is historically or architecturally important in terms of period, style, method of building construction, or associated with an important architect or builder, either by itself or in the context of a group of buildings.

18
00:01:38,389 --> 00:01:48,654
So commissioners, I sent out the link to the form B for 28 Grove Street, and I will take a motion one way or the other for this property when someone is ready.

19
00:01:50,230 --> 00:01:51,371
Uh, point of clarification.

20
00:01:52,012 --> 00:01:52,272
Yes.

21
00:01:53,033 --> 00:01:55,915
Uh, the MHC form B's are also available on our website.

22
00:01:56,235 --> 00:01:58,878
Just anybody wants to follow along.

23
00:01:59,618 --> 00:02:03,141
You just have to go to our blog page and the meeting materials are the last post.

24
00:02:04,763 --> 00:02:06,264
And that's for the next case as well.

25
00:02:06,644 --> 00:02:06,865
Yes.

26
00:02:07,545 --> 00:02:07,705
Yep.

27
00:02:08,626 --> 00:02:13,530
And on that, I will make a motion to find 28 Grove street, historically significant.

28
00:02:17,013 --> 00:02:17,574
Thank you, Ryan.

29
00:02:26,279 --> 00:02:26,900
Is there a second?

30
00:02:27,902 --> 00:02:28,423
I'll second.

31
00:02:28,924 --> 00:02:29,525
Thank you, Kit.

32
00:02:33,251 --> 00:02:35,274
OK, Ryan, I'll start with you for comments.

33
00:02:35,962 --> 00:02:40,344
Yeah, George W. Woodland did the development in this neighborhood.

34
00:02:40,384 --> 00:02:48,206
It included both Grove Street, Johnson Avenue, Tyler Avenue, and it's extended over to Sagamore Park and Sagamore Ave.

35
00:02:48,786 --> 00:03:04,152
And most of the houses built during this time period, as John Clemson notes, they're large and commodious and comfortable housing geared towards, you know, I would say white-collared individuals that were using the train, the Boston and Lowell line to commute back and forth.

36
00:03:05,372 --> 00:03:20,226
He himself is both the builder and the developer and the architect, so that's not common and that somebody undertake all three patterns and the number of housing that he built is well documented.

37
00:03:20,907 --> 00:03:25,551
In fact, his architectural books that he used, I guess, were presented

38
00:03:26,011 --> 00:03:30,954
to or brought over to on loan to the historical society within a reasonable amount of time.

39
00:03:30,975 --> 00:03:32,255
I think it was in the last two years.

40
00:03:32,836 --> 00:03:37,099
And they had the opportunity to at least possess those and copy them for a time.

41
00:03:37,559 --> 00:03:51,008
So I find that even just by itself under criteria A, which is an importantly associated with an important architect builder, both by itself and in this group of context of buildings, it's important.

42
00:03:51,428 --> 00:03:55,331
There's probably other reasons, but that's just my kickstart to the discussion here.

43
00:03:58,863 --> 00:03:59,183
That's it.

44
00:03:59,724 --> 00:04:00,404
Thank you, Ryan.

45
00:04:02,485 --> 00:04:04,947
Kit, I'll come to you next since you seconded the motion.

46
00:04:08,489 --> 00:04:22,597
So what I would say in addition to what Ryan has already said is that compared to a lot of the other properties that we look at, it's sort of remarkably original.

47
00:04:23,117 --> 00:04:26,660
So it seems like I know we can't comment on

48
00:04:28,767 --> 00:04:33,309
on sort of the state of the building, but it's largely intact.

49
00:04:34,129 --> 00:04:36,951
So it's a good example of everything that Ryan just described.

50
00:04:39,632 --> 00:04:39,932
Great.

51
00:04:40,032 --> 00:04:40,292
Yes.

52
00:04:40,472 --> 00:04:46,215
And as somebody who drives by that house every single day, I would agree with you on that.

53
00:04:46,755 --> 00:04:47,955
Ed, do you have anything to add?

54
00:04:50,016 --> 00:04:56,019
Again, as a recent pedestrian by the place without realizing it was necessarily under review, it was impressive.

55
00:04:57,189 --> 00:05:09,655
And I think, again, if you're looking at the, again, Grove is a subdivision, and also the role of the architect, I think, you know, it certainly passes significance for.

56
00:05:09,675 --> 00:05:12,857
Thank you, Ed.

57
00:05:13,397 --> 00:05:13,697
Doug?

58
00:05:15,879 --> 00:05:18,780
Yeah, I agree.

59
00:05:19,540 --> 00:05:24,103
When I look at the details, not so much about the developer and the owner, but just the details,

60
00:05:25,128 --> 00:05:26,969
you know, the elements of craftsmanship.

61
00:05:27,029 --> 00:05:28,310
This is a unique building in Mexico.

62
00:05:28,330 --> 00:05:40,997
I don't think I've seen anyone like this, and that's what makes this one, I think, fall into the significance category for me, you know, whether it's some of the shingling or the stone foundations and piers.

63
00:05:41,297 --> 00:05:46,580
This is stuff here that is unique, and we just don't see every day.

64
00:05:46,640 --> 00:05:48,621
It's not a cookie-cutter building by any stretch.

65
00:05:48,661 --> 00:05:50,202
So many of the ones in this neighborhood

66
00:05:51,297 --> 00:05:53,218
are well-crafted, unique houses.

67
00:05:53,278 --> 00:05:58,641
And that's obviously of its time period at the beginning of the 20th century.

68
00:05:58,701 --> 00:06:03,584
So I think this one's a pretty easy call for me to be put in a significant category.

69
00:06:03,664 --> 00:06:10,728
I hope we can come to a resolution quickly to bring this one back from what it clearly is, which is in tough shape, obviously.

70
00:06:10,808 --> 00:06:11,748
That's not our purview.

71
00:06:14,430 --> 00:06:15,070
Thank you, Doug.

72
00:06:15,611 --> 00:06:15,911
Peter?

73
00:06:15,931 --> 00:06:19,453
Just a point of clarification.

74
00:06:21,509 --> 00:06:30,696
On the form B, the recommended for listing in National Register of Historic Places is checked.

75
00:06:30,796 --> 00:06:32,197
Usually there's some backup to that.

76
00:06:32,217 --> 00:06:39,082
So I didn't know if that should have been checked.

77
00:06:40,383 --> 00:06:41,564
I noticed that as well.

78
00:06:41,724 --> 00:06:48,789
If it was meant to be checked, because usually he'll then back that up for these reasons or whatever.

79
00:06:52,130 --> 00:06:55,991
John may have, he sent me over another form.

80
00:06:56,091 --> 00:07:02,492
So he may not have just, he may have just not copied over the thing because it's included maybe in another form.

81
00:07:02,552 --> 00:07:04,993
He did a form for a property on Sagamore Ave.

82
00:07:06,373 --> 00:07:08,154
Let me just see if I have that form.

83
00:07:11,474 --> 00:07:14,855
Otherwise I would concur with the other commissioners.

84
00:07:16,697 --> 00:07:19,499
although it has fallen into some disrepair.

85
00:07:19,759 --> 00:07:30,045
It is largely, most of the original siding is, and detail has been preserved and hopefully can be brought back.

86
00:07:36,931 --> 00:07:37,171
Yes.

87
00:07:37,491 --> 00:07:44,115
Um, I had the same question too, on the national register checkbox and was looking for that information on the last page.

88
00:07:44,195 --> 00:07:46,437
So we'll get clarification on that.

89
00:07:47,117 --> 00:07:54,182
I think regardless, you know, um, the significance is more than warranted here.

90
00:07:54,202 --> 00:07:57,464
Um, but Jess, any comments on this one?

91
00:07:57,484 --> 00:08:00,866
I don't have anything substantive to add.

92
00:08:00,966 --> 00:08:04,528
I agree with the other commissioners and have the same question about the

93
00:08:05,790 --> 00:08:07,893
national significance piece, so yeah, thanks.

94
00:08:08,814 --> 00:08:09,254
Okay, thanks.

95
00:08:10,836 --> 00:08:22,169
Yeah, it's not included on that Sagamore Ave form, so I'll have to, maybe John was thinking, yes, we haven't done inventory for this little neighborhood, so maybe he was thinking about doing it and just didn't get around to it yet.

96
00:08:22,902 --> 00:08:24,003
Okay, we'll clarify.

97
00:08:24,023 --> 00:08:38,239
I mean, obviously, before the form goes to the state database, we'll make sure that if that it was checked in error, or if it is accurate, and we'll have them put the criteria in on the last page.

98
00:08:38,700 --> 00:08:38,880
Right.

99
00:08:40,853 --> 00:08:42,393
Okay, all right.

100
00:08:43,014 --> 00:08:48,535
So we have a motion on the table to find for significance for 28 Grove Street that has been seconded.

101
00:08:49,095 --> 00:08:54,376
I will go around for a roll call vote from the commissioners as I see folks on my screen.

102
00:08:54,837 --> 00:08:55,297
Ryan.

103
00:08:55,657 --> 00:08:55,917
Yes.

104
00:08:56,737 --> 00:08:56,917
Ed.

105
00:08:56,937 --> 00:08:58,277
Yep.

106
00:08:59,258 --> 00:08:59,538
Kit.

107
00:09:01,878 --> 00:09:02,158
Yes.

108
00:09:03,019 --> 00:09:03,339
Doug.

109
00:09:04,199 --> 00:09:04,479
Yes.

110
00:09:05,139 --> 00:09:05,519
Peter.

111
00:09:05,939 --> 00:09:06,259
Yes.

112
00:09:07,020 --> 00:09:07,540
Jessica.

113
00:09:08,300 --> 00:09:08,520
Yes.

114
00:09:09,375 --> 00:09:11,456
Okay, so the motion passes six zero.

115
00:09:12,357 --> 00:09:14,058
So the building is significant.

116
00:09:14,438 --> 00:09:17,200
We will have a preferably preserved hearing next month.

117
00:09:17,980 --> 00:09:28,646
So for the property owner, we will send you a legal notice that you will need to post a sign on front of the property and we have to post the legal notice in the newspaper as well.

118
00:09:28,766 --> 00:09:31,588
We'll need you to bring a check to city hall to cover those costs.

119
00:09:32,108 --> 00:09:38,412
I will send you an email with all of the details and your hearing will be on our next meeting on March 13th.

120
00:09:41,972 --> 00:09:42,893
Hi, this is Tasha.

121
00:09:42,913 --> 00:09:45,274
I'm the owner of Sungate Grove.

122
00:09:45,294 --> 00:09:45,935
Just a quick question.

123
00:09:45,955 --> 00:09:51,480
For next month, what should I do to prepare for the hearing?

124
00:09:52,480 --> 00:09:54,042
There's nothing you need to do to prepare.

125
00:09:54,062 --> 00:10:02,389
We will be voting whether or not the property goes under an 18-month demo delay, and we will take public comments at that meeting as well.

126
00:10:03,069 --> 00:10:05,191
But there's no presentation or anything that you have to do.

127
00:10:05,211 --> 00:10:06,532
Okay.

128
00:10:06,919 --> 00:10:12,321
Okay, so there's no record review for the renovation schemes?

129
00:10:12,741 --> 00:10:15,682
No, we don't talk about what's going to happen to the property.

130
00:10:16,122 --> 00:10:18,223
We evaluate the property as it exists.

131
00:10:19,063 --> 00:10:25,066
And then if and when there's a demo delay, then we will discuss ways to mitigate the demolition and to lift the delay.

132
00:10:26,706 --> 00:10:31,688
Okay, so the next meeting we'll review the detail for the next step.

133
00:10:33,220 --> 00:10:37,791
Next month will be a preferably preserved hearing, which is the final step in the demo delay process.

134
00:10:39,195 --> 00:10:39,395
Okay.

135
00:10:40,157 --> 00:10:40,338
Okay.

136
00:10:41,240 --> 00:10:41,480
Okay.

137
00:10:41,641 --> 00:10:41,962
Thank you.

138
00:10:46,005 --> 00:10:50,989
Okay, next up, we have a significance case for 91 Winchester Street.

139
00:10:52,010 --> 00:10:54,391
I will not review the criteria since we just did it.

140
00:10:54,992 --> 00:11:00,296
So commissioners, I will take, just to clarify this for the carriage house at 91 Winchester Street.

141
00:11:01,197 --> 00:11:03,558
Commissioners, I will take a motion when someone is ready.

142
00:11:03,578 --> 00:11:12,505
I'll motion for significance.

143
00:11:13,846 --> 00:11:14,407
Thank you, Ryan.

144
00:11:21,175 --> 00:11:23,016
I'll second for purposes of discussion.

145
00:11:23,757 --> 00:11:24,417
Thank you, Ed.

146
00:11:24,437 --> 00:11:31,422
OK, Ryan, you're up.

147
00:11:33,083 --> 00:11:49,074
In reviewing the history of this property, it's kind of interesting to see its association with the adjacent building, and although the adjacent building is no longer there, this one is still standing and it both house and carriage house are kind of maintain the same.

148
00:11:50,312 --> 00:11:57,699
look and feel and scale on this pretty generous, what I would say is a pretty generously sized parcel for this neighborhood.

149
00:11:58,860 --> 00:12:00,462
In looking at the carriage house itself,

150
00:12:02,277 --> 00:12:10,020
It, it maintains its outward appearance it's had some alterations obviously there's a block garage attached to it on the left hand side that staying.

151
00:12:10,840 --> 00:12:18,142
But it seems like the building has, you know, maintained its siding and other than the issues noted that with the roof.

152
00:12:18,542 --> 00:12:19,803
It seems like it's an okay.

153
00:12:20,823 --> 00:12:23,844
okay appearance in terms of how much historic fabric it has.

154
00:12:24,965 --> 00:12:41,450
So for that I seem and you know John Clemson and myself constantly mention that these buildings are rare and diminishing simply because they're outbuildings and they often go the way of the wind with development and you know that they

155
00:12:43,230 --> 00:12:45,351
are important reminders of a different time.

156
00:12:45,911 --> 00:12:49,073
And sooner or later, there's gonna be none of these buildings left.

157
00:12:49,153 --> 00:12:53,574
So to maintain them as best as we can is helpful.

158
00:12:53,754 --> 00:13:00,177
We'd love to see them rehabilitated, not necessarily reconstructed, but if they can be.

159
00:13:01,097 --> 00:13:08,960
But if they can't be, then having something similar, replace it so it maintains that feeling and setting would be a great help.

160
00:13:09,840 --> 00:13:12,822
We start here with determining significance and I find it significant.

161
00:13:15,343 --> 00:13:16,024
Thank you, Ryan.

162
00:13:16,044 --> 00:13:19,126
Ed, anything to add?

163
00:13:20,326 --> 00:13:22,528
I'm not going to go beyond where Ryan is.

164
00:13:22,628 --> 00:13:26,150
Again, I understand the carriage house issues are always with us.

165
00:13:28,111 --> 00:13:34,375
I also understand that we will probably be hearing more about what can and cannot be done in the next few weeks.

166
00:13:37,616 --> 00:13:37,937
All right.

167
00:13:38,057 --> 00:13:38,537
Thank you, Ed.

168
00:13:39,980 --> 00:13:41,121
Kit, anything to add here?

169
00:13:43,803 --> 00:13:45,925
Really nothing that hasn't already been said.

170
00:13:45,945 --> 00:13:58,854
I mean, it just strikes me that it is one of a limited number of examples and a diminishing number of examples of these kind of outbuildings.

171
00:14:03,098 --> 00:14:03,658
Thank you, Kit.

172
00:14:04,359 --> 00:14:04,579
Doug?

173
00:14:11,499 --> 00:14:28,167
The building itself is actually one of the better looking carriage houses I've seen in terms of most of them, by the time they get to us, sometimes they are falling down, foundations failing, been unoccupied for decades or longer.

174
00:14:28,187 --> 00:14:31,728
This one looks like it's actually in reasonable shape.

175
00:14:31,768 --> 00:14:38,351
I know we don't consider it a condition, but it seems like it's a fairly straightforward

176
00:14:40,477 --> 00:14:41,718
possible renovation product.

177
00:14:41,758 --> 00:14:50,144
Obviously, we'll find out more about it, but I do agree with the previous comments that it seems like it's very, very much intact.

178
00:14:50,204 --> 00:14:54,927
It's had some alterations, but the original character and fabric is there.

179
00:14:54,947 --> 00:14:57,309
So I'm definitely leaning towards significance.

180
00:14:57,389 --> 00:15:03,313
I'm surprised that this, is this, can you remind me if this is a teardown or a renovation?

181
00:15:03,353 --> 00:15:04,134
Can you remind me?

182
00:15:04,314 --> 00:15:05,675
Total demolition.

183
00:15:06,676 --> 00:15:09,398
Actually, they wanna keep the cinder block part

184
00:15:10,213 --> 00:15:10,713
I believe.

185
00:15:11,093 --> 00:15:12,134
And the pad, yeah.

186
00:15:12,814 --> 00:15:14,914
Yes, they want to keep it for a patio.

187
00:15:15,975 --> 00:15:31,138
Yeah, and put a patio where the carriage house is, which I'd be more in favor of the opposite of that, trying to keep the carriage house and make a patio where the cinder block one is, you know, but.

188
00:15:32,079 --> 00:15:33,699
I completely agree, Peter.

189
00:15:33,719 --> 00:15:36,880
We're tearing down the wrong side here.

190
00:15:39,145 --> 00:15:49,416
I mean, when I see something like this, I just screams like automatic in-law apartments, you know, kind of additional housing, which we're desperate to have in the city.

191
00:15:49,596 --> 00:15:55,923
But I understand I'm still getting ahead of myself, but I'm gonna definitely lean towards significance on this one.

192
00:15:55,963 --> 00:16:00,228
I just don't see another path.

193
00:16:01,503 --> 00:16:13,272
I would also like to point out, you know, it may be a small point, but the fact that this is oriented gable end to face the street is actually extremely unusual.

194
00:16:14,373 --> 00:16:26,503
This is probably of, I would say, if there's a hundred or so of these buildings left, I would say 95% of them were constructed the other way where the door is on the long end.

195
00:16:26,923 --> 00:16:27,283
And this is,

196
00:16:28,364 --> 00:16:29,205
somewhat unusual.

197
00:16:30,486 --> 00:16:31,747
And the building's kind of narrow.

198
00:16:31,807 --> 00:16:32,387
It's not deep.

199
00:16:32,727 --> 00:16:38,391
So it obviously had some sort of unusual use.

200
00:16:38,451 --> 00:16:46,617
And I'd be very interested to see the inside at some point just to see what it looks like now to see if it was changed and reoriented at one point.

201
00:16:46,697 --> 00:16:49,899
But it's just unusual to see that.

202
00:16:50,199 --> 00:16:55,823
And that's usually indicative of more agricultural barns up in northern New Hampshire and Maine.

203
00:17:01,584 --> 00:17:04,246
Peter, anything to add?

204
00:17:05,046 --> 00:17:17,212
No, I knew the former owners of this house, so my kids used to play in this yard on occasion, but I guess I have a sentimental attachment to it as well.

205
00:17:18,112 --> 00:17:27,457
I don't know if I should recuse myself or not, but it's a charming little, you know, property, you know, and I think

206
00:17:30,276 --> 00:17:32,617
The carriage house is a big part of the charm of this.

207
00:17:32,697 --> 00:17:36,780
It's almost like a little rural farm in the city.

208
00:17:36,800 --> 00:17:45,526
I think it should be preserved because it's a special little place.

209
00:17:47,167 --> 00:17:52,051
Unusual for our city, this little arrangement.

210
00:17:54,592 --> 00:17:55,213
It's all for me.

211
00:17:55,733 --> 00:17:56,394
Thank you, Peter.

212
00:17:57,214 --> 00:17:58,295
Jessica, anything to add?

213
00:18:00,327 --> 00:18:02,728
Not really great comments from all the other commissioners.

214
00:18:02,808 --> 00:18:13,094
I agree that, you know, it seems like it would be a great ADU and it's, you know, a really nice example of a diminishing building type in the city.

215
00:18:13,374 --> 00:18:16,476
So just agree with everybody else's comments.

216
00:18:20,003 --> 00:18:21,184
All right, thank you so much.

217
00:18:22,165 --> 00:18:31,952
Okay, we have a vote, excuse me, a motion on the table for 91 Winchester Street, the Carriage House for significance that has been seconded.

218
00:18:31,972 --> 00:18:37,537
I will go around and do a roll call vote as people are on my screen.

219
00:18:38,357 --> 00:18:38,777
Ryan.

220
00:18:39,138 --> 00:18:39,398
Yes.

221
00:18:40,399 --> 00:18:40,579
Ed.

222
00:18:40,599 --> 00:18:41,740
Aye.

223
00:18:42,500 --> 00:18:42,761
Kit.

224
00:18:43,721 --> 00:18:43,981
Yes.

225
00:18:44,962 --> 00:18:45,282
Doug.

226
